{"cells": [{"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "cba1e850", "metadata": {}, "source": ["# Quick start\n", "\n", "**Welcome to `bruges`!**\n", "\n", "This library does all sorts of things so it's hard to show you a single workflow and say, \"here's how to use `bruges`\". But making a simple wedge model will let us show you several features, and maybe it will help you see how to use `bruges` in your own work."]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "535b7b33", "metadata": {}, "source": ["Seismic wedge models provide seismic interpreters a quantitative way of studying thin-bed stratigraphy at or below seismic resolution. Here's the workflow:\n", "\n", "1. Define the layer geometries.\n", "1. Give those layers rock properties.\n", "1. Calculate reflection coefficients.\n", "1. Make a seismic wavelet.\n", "1. Model the seismic response by convolving the reflectivities with the wavelet. "]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 1, "id": "f367e497", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [], "source": ["import numpy as np\n", "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n", "import bruges as bg"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "a2d36f94", "metadata": {}, "source": ["## Make a wedge"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "c5010726", "metadata": {}, "source": ["The `wedge` function in `models` submodule allows you to generate a variety of stratigraphic geometries. The default gives us a model `m` which is a 2-D NumPy array of size `(100, 100)`. It has 3 layers in it."]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 2, "id": "0c940969", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [], "source": ["m, top, base, ref = bg.models.wedge()"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "0f8d35a9", "metadata": {}, "source": ["The `wedge` function returns a tuple containing the model `m`, as well as the a `top`, `base` and `ref` denoting some key boundaries in the model. Let's put these objects on a plot."]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 3, "id": "2e1c264e", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"image/png": "\n", "text/plain": ["<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"]}, "metadata": {"needs_background": "light"}, "output_type": "display_data"}], "source": ["plt.imshow(m)\n", "plt.plot(top, 'r', lw=4)\n", "plt.plot(base, 'r', lw=4)\n", "plt.axvline(ref, c='k', ls='--')\n", "plt.show()"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "109f85c9", "metadata": {}, "source": ["The model `m` is a 2-D NumPy array where each element is an index corresponding to each layer. The purple layer region has `0`, the green layer has `1` and the yellow layer is `2` . `top` and `base`, shown in red, are the depths down to the \"top\" of wedge layer and \"base\" of the wedge layer respectively. `ref` stands for \"reference trace\" and it denotes the position where the wedge has a thickness factor of 1."]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "8a3ee6be", "metadata": {}, "source": ["## Fill it with rock properties\n", "\n", "Let's define P-wave velocity, S-wave velocity, and rho (density) for our 3 rock types:"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 4, "id": "fadb7832", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [], "source": ["vps = np.array([2320, 2350, 2350])\n", "vss = np.array([1150, 1250, 1200])\n", "rhos = np.array([2650, 2600, 2620])"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "8fca63c9", "metadata": {}, "source": ["We can use these to make `vp` and `rho` earth models. We can use NumPy's fancy indexing by passing our array of indicies to access the rock properties (in this case acoustic impedance) for every element at once. "]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 5, "id": "fe130d1f", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [], "source": ["vp = vps[m]\n", "vs = vss[m]\n", "rho = rhos[m]"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "9655b6d3", "metadata": {}, "source": ["And plot the acoustic impedance to check it looks reasonable:"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 6, "id": "f10aad72", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"image/png": "\n", "text/plain": ["<Figure size 432x288 with 2 Axes>"]}, "metadata": {"needs_background": "light"}, "output_type": "display_data"}], "source": ["plt.imshow(vp*rho, interpolation='none')\n", "plt.colorbar()\n", "plt.show()"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "3ddd2689", "metadata": {}, "source": ["Or calculate the elastic impedance for a given angle `theta1`, say 10 degrees:"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 7, "id": "95ca8571", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"image/png": "\n", "text/plain": ["<Figure size 432x288 with 2 Axes>"]}, "metadata": {"needs_background": "light"}, "output_type": "display_data"}], "source": ["ei_10 = bg.rockphysics.elastic_impedance(vp, vs, rho, theta1=10)\n", "\n", "plt.imshow(ei_10, interpolation='none')\n", "plt.colorbar()\n", "plt.show()"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "527dbcba", "metadata": {}, "source": ["We can even compute the EI for a whole bunch of angles at once, like `np.arange(0, 31)` (31 angles, from 0 to 30 degrees). The result is a 3D reflection coefficient volume:"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 8, "id": "bf19d608", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"text/plain": ["(30, 100, 100)"]}, "execution_count": 8, "metadata": {}, "output_type": "execute_result"}], "source": ["ei = bg.rockphysics.elastic_impedance(vp, vs, rho, theta1=np.arange(30))\n", "\n", "ei.shape"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "b10217cb", "metadata": {}, "source": ["We can plot the wedge at any angle:"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 9, "id": "499f26c8", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"image/png": "\n", "text/plain": ["<Figure size 432x288 with 2 Axes>"]}, "metadata": {"needs_background": "light"}, "output_type": "display_data"}], "source": ["plt.imshow(ei[25], interpolation='none')\n", "plt.colorbar()\n", "plt.show()"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "ba840b06", "metadata": {}, "source": ["## Calculate acoustic reflectivity"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "4de05639", "metadata": {}, "source": ["We can create a section of normal incidence reflection coefficient. This will be what we convolve with a wavelet. \n", "\n", "Bruges can calculate the acoustic reflectivity:"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 10, "id": "bec928ac", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"image/png": "\n", "text/plain": ["<Figure size 432x288 with 2 Axes>"]}, "metadata": {"needs_background": "light"}, "output_type": "display_data"}], "source": ["rc = bg.reflection.acoustic_reflectivity(vp, rho)\n", "\n", "plt.imshow(rc)\n", "plt.colorbar()\n", "plt.show()"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "13a7e032", "metadata": {}, "source": ["The reflections coeffients are zero almost everywhere, except at the layer boundaries. The reflection coefficient between layer 1 and layer 2 is a negative, and between layer 2 and layer 3 is a positive number. This will determine the scale and polarity of the seismic amplitudes. "]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "17f90ffe", "metadata": {}, "source": ["## Offset reflectivity\n", "\n", "We can also calculate the exact Zoeppritz offset reflectivity. For example, to compute the reflectivity at 10 degrees of offset &mdash; note that this results in complex numbers, so we'll only use the real part in the plot:"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 11, "id": "a382edf4", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"image/png": "\n", "text/plain": ["<Figure size 432x288 with 2 Axes>"]}, "metadata": {"needs_background": "light"}, "output_type": "display_data"}], "source": ["rc_10 = bg.reflection.reflectivity(vp, vs, rho, theta=10)\n", "\n", "plt.imshow(rc_10.real)\n", "plt.colorbar()\n", "plt.show()"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "3c2cdc49", "metadata": {}, "source": ["As with the elastic impedance calculation, we can create a range of angles at once:"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 12, "id": "2a2b0fa4", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"text/plain": ["(60, 100, 100)"]}, "execution_count": 12, "metadata": {}, "output_type": "execute_result"}], "source": ["rc = bg.reflection.reflectivity(vp, vs, rho, theta=np.arange(60), method='shuey')\n", "\n", "rc.shape"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "4e4b940e", "metadata": {}, "source": ["The 10-degree reflectivity we computed before is in there as `rc[10]`, but we can also see how reflectivity varies with angle:"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 13, "id": "527f0e6d", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"image/png": "\n", "text/plain": ["<Figure size 864x360 with 2 Axes>"]}, "metadata": {"needs_background": "light"}, "output_type": "display_data"}], "source": ["offset = 10  # degrees\n", "trace = 60\n", "\n", "fig, axs = plt.subplots(ncols=2, figsize=(12, 5), sharey=True)\n", "axs[0].imshow(rc[offset].real, vmin=-0.01, vmax=0.01)\n", "axs[0].axvline(trace, c='k', ls='--')\n", "axs[1].imshow(rc[:, :, trace].real.T, vmin=-0.01, vmax=0.01)\n", "axs[1].axvline(offset, c='k', ls='--')\n", "plt.show()"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "769c969a", "metadata": {}, "source": ["## Create a wavelet\n", "\n", "Let's create a Ricker wavelet to serve as our seismic pulse. We specify it has a length of 0.256 s, a sample interval of 0.002 s, and corner frequencies of 8, 12, 20, and 40 Hz:"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 14, "id": "ba90e362", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"text/plain": ["[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7fb70c9b4970>]"]}, "execution_count": 14, "metadata": {}, "output_type": "execute_result"}, {"data": {"image/png": "\n", "text/plain": ["<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"]}, "metadata": {"needs_background": "light"}, "output_type": "display_data"}], "source": ["w, t = bg.filters.ricker(0.064, 0.001, 40)\n", "\n", "plt.plot(t, w)"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "259b9e8c", "metadata": {}, "source": ["There are several wavelet functions; they can all take a sequence of frequencies and produce all of them at once as a filter bank:"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 15, "id": "5248f4d9", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"text/plain": ["Text(0, 0.5, 'frequency [Hz]')"]}, "execution_count": 15, "metadata": {}, "output_type": "execute_result"}, {"data": {"image/png": "\n", "text/plain": ["<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"]}, "metadata": {"needs_background": "light"}, "output_type": "display_data"}], "source": ["w_bank, t = bg.filters.ricker(0.096, 0.001, np.arange(12, 80))\n", "\n", "plt.imshow(w_bank)\n", "plt.xlabel('time [samples]')\n", "plt.ylabel('frequency [Hz]')"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "2c3fcfc7", "metadata": {}, "source": ["## Convolve the wavelet with the reflectivity"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "6d390eae", "metadata": {}, "source": ["We can use `bruges` to perform a convolution.\n", "\n", "Remember our RC series is 3D. Let's keep it simple for now and look at a single waveform from the reference location `ref` in our model. The synthetic seismic trace is band-limited filtering of the reflectivity spikes. When these spikes get closer together the waveforms will \"tune\" with one another and won't necessarily line up with the reflectivity series."]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 16, "id": "6ff4c5fa", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"image/png": "\n", "text/plain": ["<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"]}, "metadata": {"needs_background": "light"}, "output_type": "display_data"}], "source": ["rc_ref = rc[0, :, ref]\n", "\n", "syn = bg.filters.convolve(rc_ref, w)\n", "\n", "plt.plot(rc_ref)\n", "plt.plot(syn)\n", "plt.show()"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "795c94dc", "metadata": {}, "source": ["In the 1D case, it would have been easy enough to use `np.convolve` to do this. The equivalent code is:\n", "\n", "    syn = np.convolve(rc_ref, w, mode='same')\n", "\n", "But when the reflectivity is two-dimensional, you need to use `np.apply_along_axis` or some other trick to essentially loop over the traces. But don't worry! The `bruges` function will compute the convolution for you over all of the dimensions at once:"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 17, "id": "1557de40", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"text/plain": ["(60, 100, 100)"]}, "execution_count": 17, "metadata": {}, "output_type": "execute_result"}], "source": ["syn = bg.filters.convolve(rc, w)\n", "\n", "syn.shape"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "3f872b7d", "metadata": {}, "source": ["Remember those are offsets in the first dimension. Let's look at the zero-offset synthetic alongside the 30-degree panel:"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 18, "id": "03366ba8", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"image/png": "\n", "text/plain": ["<Figure size 864x360 with 2 Axes>"]}, "metadata": {"needs_background": "light"}, "output_type": "display_data"}], "source": ["# A quick way to set a sensible max, so both panels have the same colours.\n", "ma = np.percentile(syn, 99.9)\n", "\n", "near, far = 0, 30\n", "\n", "fig, axs = plt.subplots(ncols=2, figsize=(12, 5))\n", "axs[0].imshow(syn[near], cmap='seismic_r', vmin=-ma, vmax=ma)\n", "axs[0].set_title(f'{near} degrees')\n", "axs[1].imshow(syn[far], cmap='seismic_r', vmin=-ma, vmax=ma)\n", "axs[1].set_title(f'{far} degrees')\n", "plt.show()"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "1588b0b5", "metadata": {}, "source": ["Or we could look at a single 'angle gather':"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 19, "id": "e42e16ea", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"text/plain": ["Text(0.5, 0, 'angle')"]}, "execution_count": 19, "metadata": {}, "output_type": "execute_result"}, {"data": {"image/png": "\n", "text/plain": ["<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"]}, "metadata": {"needs_background": "light"}, "output_type": "display_data"}], "source": ["trace = 70\n", "\n", "plt.imshow(syn[:, :, trace].T)\n", "plt.xlabel('angle')"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "a8d20832", "metadata": {}, "source": ["## Bend your mind\n", "\n", "The convolution function will also accept a filter bank (a collection of wavelets at different frequencies). We made one earlier called `w_bank`.\n", "\n", "Watch out: the result of this convolution will be 4-dimensional!"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "execution_count": 20, "id": "558b9426", "metadata": {}, "outputs": [{"data": {"text/plain": ["(68, 60, 100, 100)"]}, "execution_count": 20, "metadata": {}, "output_type": "execute_result"}], "source": ["syn = bg.filters.convolve(rc, w_bank)\n", "\n", "syn.shape"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "7db3b39c", "metadata": {}, "source": ["So we can look at the synthetic created with a 22 Hz wavelet (the wavelet bank started at 12 Hz, so this is slice {"text/plain": ["<matplotlib.image.AxesImage at 0x7fb70c8a0520>"]}, "execution_count": 23, "metadata": {}, "output_type": "execute_result"}, {"data": {"image/png": "\n", "text/plain": ["<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"]}, "metadata": {"needs_background": "light"}, "output_type": "display_data"}], "source": ["plt.imshow(syn[10, 30])"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "id": "ea14a7b1", "metadata": {},
